This is where the intuition gets very sharp, but also where physics forces a subtle shift.

The short answer is:

It isn’t stored somewhere like an object in a container.
It exists in the configuration of the system itself.

Let’s unpack that.

⸻

1. We instinctively look for a “place”

Our brains expect properties to live inside something:
	•	water in a cup
	•	files in a folder
	•	energy in a battery

So when we hear “potential energy,” it feels like there must be a location where it’s stored.

But many physical properties are relational, not locational.

⸻

2. Example: gravitational potential

Imagine a rock on a cliff.

Where is the potential energy?

Not purely in:
	•	the rock
	•	the Earth
	•	the space between them

It exists in the configuration: rock + Earth + distance + gravity.

If you change the distance, the potential changes instantly.

So the property belongs to the relationship.

⸻

3. Think of it like geometry

Potential is closer to shape than to a substance.

Example:

A bowl.

The bowl’s shape determines how a marble will roll.

Where is the “rolling behavior” stored?

Not anywhere physically.

It’s encoded in the geometry of the surface.

⸻

4. Physics describes this with fields

Modern physics says properties like potential are part of fields.

Examples:
	•	gravitational field
	•	electric field
	•	quantum fields

Fields assign a value to every point in space describing how a particle would behave there.

So the “storage” is actually the state of the field across space.

⸻

5. Another perspective: information

A lot of physicists describe potential energy as information about possible motion.

Example:

A stretched spring contains information that says:

if released → it will contract

That rule is encoded in:
	•	molecular bonds
	•	geometry
	•	forces

Again, it’s not a separate thing sitting somewhere — it’s the structure of the system.

⸻

